			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Now recruiting:  Please submit your resume for consideration.<a name="58953"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 25 04 1:55 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>If 50 or so folks are serious enough about the game to dedicate 4-5 hours a night to it, and make a guild,  then they have a right to work recruitment however they want.  If you think their recruitment policies are silly or to detailed, then dont join that guild, it is pretty simple.  It sounds to me like you are pissed at some folks who left your guild to progress in the game.  Every time anyone leaves a guild to jump to a &quot;higher tier&quot; guild, folks always get pissed.  It is a fact of EQ, it will always happen. 
<br />

<br />
 What really sucks is if folks leave immediately after a major milestone has been acheived (IE: RZ kill), or major piece of gear has been awarded them (Aten Ha Ra Neck, Cursed BP).  If that happens, then bitch away, Im with ya.  But if they just left your guild to progress in game, then the best thing you can do is send em a tell to keep in touch, say hi when ya see em in game, and continue on and enjoy the game without them.
<br />

<br />
All RPGs, online or offline, solo or MMPORG, share a common theme of character progression.  You start with a relatively blank slate, and build the character up through equipment and/or skill selections.  Doing the same thing over and over gets boring after a while.  EQ can be just a chatroom with pretty graphics if you want, but it can also be an engrossing and challenging game that rewards large groups of folks who spend time online working together.
<br />

<br />
Once you have beaten EMP SSRA a few times, or tore through NToV a bit, then going back again and again seems to go AGAINST the idea of role playing doesnt it?  I mean, you can get AA exp, but that is about it.  If you want to see Rallos Zek the Warlord, or Fennin Ro, you have to make the commitment.  If you want to equip you character with better gear, then you have to make the commitment.  Folks who spend a lot of time playing and learning to work together arent likely to just hand out flags to someone who spends a few hours a week in Bot.  You have to jump through some hoops, spend a lot of time in game, and risk alienating folks you used to socilaize in game with.  If it is worth all that, then you will send in the letters and magelos.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
