				<td colspan="2"><span>I have found that applications are a needed part to guild recruitment.  However, the type of application I am talking about focus on how the person plays, their personality and the such.  These types of applications let the guild know right off the bat the kind of person they are dealing with and an initial expectation during a probationary phase.
<br />
Some guilds go beyond this and require nearly corporate resume's and they're noses are just pegged into the content they're currently exploring and won't have anything to do with anyone slightly incapable of that content.  For some this is acceptable and they don't mind the scrutinization put upon them to experience that particular piece of content.
<br />
On the other hand there are others that want an environment not biased towards who has the better gear or who zerged what uber mob.  
<br />
The glorious thing about this game is that we all fit into different game play styles and those of common like tend to find eachother, hang out and form or join guilds of similar like.
<br />
Just because someone you have come to friend in game leaves a guild to play the game the way they want to does not neccessarily mean they have revoked their friendship with you.  You might not be a part of their main ciricle, but you can still remain friends and do things if you chose to.</span></td>
